		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2017"></a><br><code>sle2017/paper11</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2017</a> paper:</span><br><i>Ensuring non-interference of composable language extensions</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/TedKaminski.html">Ted Kaminski</a>, <a href="../profile/EricVanWyk.html">Eric Van Wyk</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3136014.3136023">10.1145/3136014.3136023</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagM">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The paper is about composing independent language extensions and ensuring they do not interfere.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5d.html"><span class="tagL">T5D: Formal Methods</span></a><ul><li> Non-interference properties are framed and justified with formal criteria/arguments.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1b.html"><span class="tagL">T1B: Static Semantics</span></a><ul><li> Guaranteeing extension safety often relies on static checks (e.g., typing/discipline) that the paper builds on.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4c.html"><span class="tagL">T4C: Vertical Transformation</span></a><ul><li> The setting typically assumes compiler construction mechanisms for combining extensions into an executable toolchain.
</li></ul></li></ul>
